The paper deals with biasing Boolean functions and collective coin flipping protocols, which are topics in computational complexity theory and information theory. The use of coalitions and product measures suggests connections to game theory and probability theory, which are also relevant subfields of computer science. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CC (Computational Complexity), followed by cs.IT (Information Theory), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory).
